{
  "text": "Notch is a plasma membrane receptor involved in the control of cell fate specification and in the maintenance of the proliferative/ differentiative balance in many cell lineages [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , and alterations in Notch signaling have been implicated in tumorigenesis [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . However, with the exception of a rare translocation in T cell malignancies [CITATION_6] , no genetic lesion of the Notch locus has been described in human tumors. Increased Notch signaling profoundly impairs normal mammary gland morphogenesis in mice, promoting the rapid development of poorly differentiated adenocarcinomas [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . This finding raises the possibility that subversion of Notch signaling might play a role in human breast tumors; yet little direct evidence for such an involvement has been provided so far [CITATION_9] . Thus, one major question is whether and how Notch is altered in human breast tumors, and how deregulation of its signaling might contribute to the neoplastic phenotype.",
